start: ^ Joe, you don't have a dog, do you?
^ Alice?! What the hell?! Where have you been??
^ You know. On the run. I died.
^ Again? What is it this time? Another apocalypse?
^ That's the thing - I can't remember. But I think future me is trying to remind me. I've got these...files.
^ What are you talking about? Last time you dreamt, there was music...
^ And the end of the world. No, this is something else. The dog?
^ ...it's always so freaky when you do this. No, I don't have a dog, but I am going to take care of my mum's dog, Jackie, next week.
^I still can't believe this is happening...

c-0: ^ Uhhh. Soo...my desktop is behaving really strangely. It's full of files that I'm pretty sure are dated in the future.
^ Yup. But they're not...whole. It's like my patchy memory when I kept waking up before the apocalypse, remember?
^ Nope, this is new. But I found that if I can...recall certain trigger words associated with the files, they become clearer.
c-1: ^ This is weird, even by your standards, Alice.
g-0: ^ Yeahh....I feel like I might have fallen into an even deeper rabbit hole this time.
^ But with your help, I'm sure I'll figure it out. Before I die again...

tutorial: ^Any word in the file helps! Even a little!
^Look for names, places, concepts for trigger words!
^Words not in the text CAN be trigger words too! (for example: in images)
^Careful with guessing: wrong guesses lead to decoherence!
^Trigger words for this: alice (that's me!) and 'mystery'.

win: ^ Good to know I can still follow my own instructions...

^Alice: I am! You have no idea how hard it is to convince people I am not crazy, but Professor Forrest seems to actually believe me!
^MadHatter: Are you sure they're not with...you know?

^You've stressed your need for discretion, so I have embedded the code to the campus side entrance into the picture - that way you do not have to go through the lobby at all!

^ Hmm. That doesn't sound like you. You're usually a lot more careful around people.
lose: ^ That was a dead end. Damn.

lose: ^ You probably really needed that to continue, you know.

interview1: ^I: Describe how it feels to remember the future.
^AC: Like a dream. I wake up, and I dreamt the future.
^I: In the dream, do you ever remember having had the dream of the future before?
^AC: No, which is funny now that you mention it. But sometimes I change what I do in the dream without really knowing why - except when I wake up I do know why I did it.
^I: Are you familiar with the concept of a Quantum Echo?

lose: ^ Nope. This is all just noise now...

interview2: ^I: Imagine shouting into a room, closing the door, and then coming back later and hearing the echo of your own voice.
^I: And this is how you'd remember and record information.
^AC: For making notes, I prefer pen and paper.
^I: Except we can't record quantum information on pen and paper. But we may be able to do it using other methods, like sound.
^AC: There is a song that plays sometimes...

win: ^ Okay, so they're suggesting the song is somehow connected to...something.
^ The song? Oh, right. The song. 'When logic and proportion have fallen sloppy dead'...
^ What are you up to, future Alice...
lose: ^ I'm not getting anything more out of this one...

interview3: ^I: But the song hasn't been working as well any longer, right?
^AC: Mm. I think it was connected to the Veteran, not me.
^AC: But now that that's me, I might need my own music?
^I: Or other sounds. That's the experiment we'll be doing here at QPAC.

win: ^ Experiments! We're doing experiments! On music, it seems.
^ I feel like I can almost remember...
lose: ^ Hopefully nothing of value was lost!
